<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
When you use another person&#8217;s ideas or words in your writing, include the author&#8217;s name and any relevant page number(s), in parentheses, immediately following the cited material. When there are two or more works by the same author, also include the title in italics.
<br><br>
In a parenthetical citation, include the title of the work in italics, and the relevant page number(s), in parentheses, immediately following the cited material. Abbreviate the title if it is longer than a noun phrase. For example, <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Southern Novels</em> consists entirely of a noun phrase (a noun <em>Novels</em> preceded by two modifiers) and wouldnâ€™t be shortened. By contrast <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Novels of the South</em> would be shortened to its noun phrase <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Novels</em>. The abbreviated title should begin with the word by which it is alphabetised in the Works Cited. If the title does not begin with a noun phrase, cite the first word if it is enough to direct the reader to the correct entry. For further information on abbreviating titles, see 3.2.1 in the <a href="http://west-sydney-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/UWS-ALMA:default_scope:UWS-ALMA21186157620001571" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">MLA Handbook (8th edition)</a>. 
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;was found to be the case (Smith, <em>Exploring</em> 25&#45;26)
</blockquote>
<br>
Or include the author&#8217;s name in your sentence, with the title and relevant page number(s) in parentheses.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Smith suggests that &#34;the default position is markedly affected&#34; 	(<em>Exploring</em> 23).
</blockquote>
<br>
When the author is referred to more than once in the same paragraph only the page number is needed for subsequent citations, as long as the work cannot be confused with others cited.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;was found to be the case (Smith, <em>Exploring</em> 23). 
	In addition&hellip; was a common feature (26).
</blockquote>
